rt by using the double-angle identity for cosine, which states that \\(\\cos 2\\theta = \\frac{1 - \\tan^2 \\theta}{1 + \\tan^2 \\theta}\\). Let \\(x = \\tan^2 \\theta\\). Then we have:\n\\[\n\\cos 2\\theta = \\frac{1 - x}{1 + x}.\n\\]\nWe are given that \\(\\cos 2\\theta = \\frac{1 + \\sqrt{5}}{4}\\), so we can set up the equation:\n\\[\n\\frac{1 - x}{1 + x} = \\frac{1 + \\sqrt{5}}{4}.\n\\]\nTo solve for \\(x\\), we cross-multiply to get:\n\\[\n4(1 - x) = (1 + \\sqrt{5})(1 + x).\n\\]\nExpanding both sides, we get:\n\\[\n4 - 4x = 1 + x + \\sqrt{5} + \\sqrt{5}x.\n\\]\nRearranging terms to isolate \\(x\\), we get:\n\\[\n4 - 1 - \\sqrt{5} = x + 4x + \\sqrt{5}x,\n\\]\n\\[\n3 - \\sqrt{5} = x(1 + 4 + \\sqrt{5}),\n\\]\n\\[\n3 - \\sqrt{5} = x(5 + \\sqrt{5}).\n\\]\nSolving for \\(x\\), we get:\n\\[\nx = \\frac{3 - \\sqrt{5}}{5 + \\sqrt{5}}.\n\\]\nTo rationalize the denominator, we multiply the numerator and the denominator by the conjugate of the denominator:\n\\[\nx = \\frac{(3 - \\sqrt{5})(5 - \\sqrt{5})}{(5 + \\sqrt{5})(5 - \\sqrt{5})} = \\frac{15 - 3\\sqrt{5} - 5\\sqrt{5} + 5}{25 - 5} = \\frac{20 - 8\\sqrt{5}}{20} = \\frac{5 - 2\\sqrt{5}}{5}.\n\\]\nThus, \\(\\tan^2 \\theta = \\frac{5 - 2\\sqrt{5}}{5}\\).\n\nNext, we need to find \\(\\tan^2 3\\theta\\). Using the triple-angle identity for tangent, we have:\n\\[\n\\tan 3\\theta = \\frac{3\\tan \\theta - \\tan^3 \\theta}{1 - 3\\tan^2 \\theta}.\n\\]\nLet \\(y = \\tan \\theta\\). Then \\(\\tan^2 \\theta = y^2 = \\frac{5 - 2\\sqrt{5}}{5}\\), so \\(y = \\pm \\sqrt{\\frac{5 - 2\\sqrt{5}}{5}}\\). Therefore, \\(\\tan^3 \\theta = y^3 = \\left( \\pm \\sqrt{\\frac{5 - 2\\sqrt{5}}{5}} \\right)^3 = \\pm \\frac{(5 - 2\\sqrt{5})\\sqrt{5 - 2\\sqrt{5}}}{5\\sqrt{5}}\\). However, we can use the identity \\(\\tan 3\\theta = \\frac{3y - y^3}{1 - 3y^2}\\) directly to find \\(\\tan^2 3\\theta\\):\n\\[\n\\tan^2 3\\theta = \\left( \\frac{3y - y^3}{1 - 3y^2} \\right)^2 = \\left( \\frac{3 \\pm \\sqrt{\\frac{5 - 2\\sqrt{5}}{5}} - \\left( \\pm \\frac{